                                        <assignee username="-1">Unassigned</assignee>
                                    <reporter username="supun">Supun Kamburugamuva</reporter>
                        <labels>
                    </labels>
                <created>Thu, 6 May 2010 11:36:07 +0000</created>
                <updated>Fri, 7 May 2010 05:10:16 +0000</updated>
                            <resolved>Fri, 7 May 2010 05:10:16 +0000</resolved>
                                                                        <due></due>
                            <votes>0</votes>
                                    <watches>0</watches>
                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="12864737" author="supun" created="Thu, 6 May 2010 11:39:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Added base64Encode Xpath function to synapse.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12864853" author="veithen" created="Thu, 6 May 2010 17:38:24 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Since base64 is an encoding scheme for binary data, the XPath function either needs an encoding argument, or it should use a standard encoding such as UTF-8. Using String#getBytes() is a programming error (except when preparing data for communication with other processes on the same system) because it uses the platform&apos;s default charset encoding. The same is true for new String(byte[]).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12865019" author="supun" created="Fri, 7 May 2010 04:33:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for pointing this out. I&apos;ll improve the function to add the charset as a argument to the function as well and use the default as UTF-8.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thanks,&lt;br/&gt;
Supun..&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12865024" author="supun" created="Fri, 7 May 2010 05:10:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Added a second argument to the encode function. If the second argument is not specified we use the UTF-8 encoding.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
